snippet.textDisplay: We bought one of these Silhouette's in 1991 when they first came out.  The styling was for aerodynamics but also it was cool and futuristic - and at the time Olds was innovating style across their line with these space-ship looks - the Cutlass had some and the new luxury sedan Aurora.  The car was under-powered and worse - the drive-train was just not tough enough to handle the way people used these vehicles - it had incredible space and you could strap stuff to the roof - so we had three kids - pulled out two of the seats strategically  (taking out one in second row middle and one in third row - so each kid has his/her own personal space... any Mom/Dad who hauls little  kids more than 20 minute trips knows how valuable that can be. ) The seats in the Chrysler were a bench - so only way to seat five and use rest for storage was pull out a 70 pound bench .  My wife could fold up and pull out any of the 35 pound seats easily and they stored more easily.  We liked it enough we bought another one in 1996 with more upgrades and luxury (better engine and leather)... Problem with these was the transmission - it was overtaxed by overloading the vehicles in a car that was really just a Cutlass or Lumina underneath.  Our second minivan stranded us when the transmission gears blew apart in the transmission (at about 65,000 miles)  - with us 700 miles from home with a full load of kids and travel gear.  We replaced it with a Buick Rendezvous (yes my wife liked quirky styled vehicles - her first car was my mother-in-law's yellow AMC Pacer in 1975 - so it is genetic).  The Rendezvous and the Chevy and Pontiac cousins are not around any longer because they were workhorses - families abused these things - then sold them to new families who abused them - all mini-vans were like that - but this one had transmission issues - ask most people who had them and their transmission was probably the thing that caused them to give it up.

snippet.textDisplay:
I had the pleasure of driving a 1992 Silhouette with the 3800 engine in High School and College. Some fun/unusual facts that were missed:
1. All reasonably priced cars in the 90's sucked, in 1992 the silhouette with the 3800 engine as actually the most powerful minivan out there, in high school I would regularly out accelerate my friends with "normal" cars like accords and civics.
2. They came with a built in air compressor in the drivers side rear hatch side, it was insanely powerful and useful. The van needed it because at least the version I had, had rear air bag suspension for heavy loads. If you removed the two rear seats and folded the middle three forward you could fit five 1/2 kegs of beer in the rear of the van. At this point the compressor was running continuously the whole ride home to fill the air bags.
3. The best trick of all: Use the windshield squirters and shoot washer fluid all over the front windshield, then quickly turn the massive wipers on the fastest setting. In this manner you could shoot washer fluid a clear 15-20 ft to side of the car soaking innocent bystanders.
